# Arc 0026 — narrative summary

> **This is not a substitute for stats.** It is the narrative companion to the
> numbers the stats tool computes (token/cost/timing/per-slice figures); read the
> two together. This file is prose only — the story the structured impl-logs and
> `.manifest-arc-runner.log` do not tell.

## How it went, in one line

Six of seven slices landed green and unattended; slice 007 escalated on a
genuinely-trivial cosmetic defect and was closed by hand + `accept-current-slice`.
The arc is COMPLETE.

## The uneventful part (001–006)

Slices 001 through 006 — the geometry/placement domain model, the ray/snapping
model, localization (EN/RU), the optical-table rendering geometry, the centralized
commands + constructor MVU surface, and the ribbon/menu shell — committed cleanly
across roughly nine hours with no operator intervention and nothing the supervisor
flagged as surprising. From the supervisor's vantage these were ordinary green
slices; their internal decisions live in their own impl-logs.

## The slice-007 story (the part worth remembering)

Slice 007 (element groups, experiment collections, multiple detectors, undo/redo)
escalated with **all seven gates green**. The code-judge routed back twice over a
single narrow defect: the no-op undo-snapshot guard was not actually uniform while
the state-of-the-world asserted it was. Cycle 1 had correctly steered the worker to
route `editActive` through the `commitIfChanged` guard so an inert edit pushes no
empty `Ctrl+Z` step — but two sibling commit sites, `resetRotationNow` and
`setPrimaryDetectorNow`, were left on the unconditional `commit`. Confirming
reset-rotation on an already-zero element, or "Set as primary" on the
already-primary (index-0) detector, therefore still pushed an empty undo step — the
exact no-op-push the slice's own High risk (AC-K1) forbids. The SoW meanwhile
claimed "the guard is now UNIFORM," a claim the diff contradicted; on the arc's
final slice (which carries the closing baseline) the judge declined to rubber-stamp
a SoW that overstated the very property the review loop had been gating.

The defect itself was real but **cosmetic** — an empty undo step, not data loss —
and the architecture critic was ship-leaning. What turned a "one cheap re-spawn
away" fix into a red arc was a budget accident: an earlier worker `exit 1` crash,
unrelated to any review finding, consumed a per-slice failure slot. That forced the
slice's single resolver run early, so when the cycle-2 route-back arrived the
resolver cap was already spent and the supervisor escalated instead of re-spawning.

## Resolution and the decision behind it

We chose to **hand-fix** rather than restart the arc or issue an operator-reply.
A plain restart was the wrong call: it would re-enter slice 007 with no steering
and the resolver budget already spent, re-creating the exact escalation conditions
(the worker would re-attempt against code + SoW that already *claimed* to be done).
An operator-reply (injecting the judge's `retry_hint`) was sound but became
redundant once the fix — two one-line changes the judge had specified verbatim,
plus two regression tests mirroring the existing locked-axis no-op test, plus the
SoW correction — was applied and verified directly (build clean; ui-tests 88→90;
ui-smoke, constructor and unit gates green). Slice 007 was then closed with
`accept-current-slice`, completing the arc.

## Things a future reader should know

- **The slice-007 SHA in the state file is misleading.** `accept-current-slice`
  commits "whatever's dirty," and the only dirty file at boot was the supervisor's
  own `.supervisor-lock.diag`. So the recorded slice-007 commit points at a
  one-line diag-file change, **not** the code fix. The actual fix lives in the
  preceding manual commit (message "0026-07 - Manual"), flagged `manual: true`.
  Chase the fix through history, not through the recorded SHA.

- **Two stale beliefs were corrected mid-run.** (1) The postmortem claimed the
  per-slice failure budget had to be "topped up" before re-spawning — it does not;
  that counter resets every launch, and only `total_route_backs` and
  `resolver_runs` persist across launches. (2) The arc-runner launcher doc says
  `accept-current-slice` "validates the worktree is clean" — that precondition was
  removed in the actual code, which now commits the dirty tree (porcelain-as-truth).

- **The root irritant was process, not design.** An unrelated worker crash counting
  against the per-slice failures cap is a sharp edge: it spent the rescue budget
  that would otherwise have absorbed a trivial cycle-2 fix on the final slice. If
  that accounting is ever revisited, this arc is the motivating example.
